Introduction and Background¶

As a group of cinephiles, we decided to perform analysis on data on movies and movie reviews. There are many different aspects to investigate in regards to movie data, so we decided to start with a broad analysis goal, and once we gain some insight, we narrowed down some specific relationships to investigate. We found two different datasets collected from IMDB, and a large dataset of separate user reviews.

Datasets we used:¶

https://www.kaggle.com/carolzhangdc/imdb-5000-movie-dataset https://www.kaggle.com/PromptCloudHQ/imdb-data/data https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/

First import the following libraries that we'll be using throughout this tutorial:

1.1 Lets clean up the movies data from movies.csv¶

In [2]:
#Extract the year from the title column
year, title1, title_length = [], [], []
for i in range (len(movies)):
    title = movies['title'][i][0:-7]
    year.append(movies['title'][i][-5:-1])
    title1.append(title)
    title_length.append(len(title.split()))
movies['title'] = title1
movies['title_length'] = title_length
movies['year'] = year

#change some of the titles to not have (blah..) in the middle
reg = re.compile('\(.*\)')
movies['title'] = movies['title'].str.replace(reg,'',regex=True)

#change some of the titles to not have have form: 'Movie Title, The'
movies['title'] = movies['title'].map(lambda x: str(x)).map(lambda x: x if ',' not in x else x[x.rfind(',') + 1:] + " " + x[:x.rfind(',')])

#merge movies with links to get the imdb id's
movies = movies.merge(links, how='inner', on='movieId')

movies["genres"] = (movies["genres"].map(lambda x: str(x))).map(lambda x: x if x == 'NaN' else x.replace('|', ','))
movies.drop(axis=1,inplace=True,columns=['tmdbId'])

1.3 Tidy up and create an IMBD movie dataset¶

This dataset has all of the meta data about our movies, and is a combination of 2 imdb datasets. These datasets we named meta1 and meta 2. Becuase we are combining these two sets and they have similar but not exactly matching data and formats, some values are missing

In [6]:
# For meta2, extract the imbd movie ids from inside the link and put into a new column
regex = re.compile(r"\/tt(\d+)")
ids = []
for i in range (len(meta2)):
    match = re.search(regex, meta2['movie_imdb_link'][i])
    ids.append(match.group(1))
meta2['IMDB_ID'] = ids

In [8]:
#format some of the columns
    # Year column
meta2["Year"] = meta2["title_year"].map(lambda x: str(x)).map(lambda x: 0 if x == 'NaN' else x[:4])
meta2.drop(axis=1,columns=['title_year'], inplace=True)
    # duration column
meta2["Runtime (Minutes)"] = meta2['duration'].map(lambda x: str(x)).map(lambda x: 0 if x == 'NaN' else x[:4])
meta2.drop(axis=1,columns=['duration'], inplace=True)
    # Actor column
meta2['Actors'] = meta2['actor_1_name'] + ', ' + meta2['actor_2_name'] + ', ' + meta2['actor_3_name']
meta2.drop(axis=1, inplace=True,columns=['actor_1_name', 'actor_2_name', 'actor_3_name'])
    # gross column
meta2["Revenue (Millions)"] = meta2["gross"].map(lambda x: str(x)).map(lambda x: 0 if x == 'NaN' else float(x)/1000000)
meta2.drop(axis=1, inplace=True,columns=['gross'])
    # genre column
meta2["Genre"] = (meta2["genres"].map(lambda x: str(x))).map(lambda x: x if x == 'NaN' else x.replace('|', ','))
meta2.drop(axis=1,columns=['genres'], inplace=True)
    # title column
meta2["Title"] = (meta2["movie_title"].map(lambda x: str(x))).map(lambda x: x if x == 'NaN' else x.replace(u'\xa0', u''))
meta2.drop(axis=1,columns=['movie_title'], inplace=True)
    # Rename some columns
meta2.rename(columns={'director_name' : 'Director', 'imdb_score' : 'Rating'}, inplace=True) 
   

imdb_table = pd.concat([meta1, meta2], axis=0, sort=False, join='outer') #The magic

#Drop duplicate movies
imdb_table.drop_duplicates(subset='Title', keep="last", inplace=True)

Lets talk about our master movie meta data dataframe:¶

We have over 5000 movies that have data on everything from the director of the movie to its runtime and revenue. There are definitely some holes that must be addressed however. First off, there are may more than 5000 movies in existence, so this is only a taste. We are also missing some data. Much of it is no doubt due the limits on our data quantity, but some of it may be missing not at random. In particular, there are some movies that do not have data on revenue. It could be missing at random and be dependant on the movies imdb rating, or the data could be missing not at random because the revenue was low and thus was not reported. Also, analysis on the relationship between budget and gross revenue can't really be explored because we only have budget data for a few number of movies. Like wise, many relationships could not be explore fully due to large sums of missing data.

Plot 2.1.4 Decade vs Revenue Violin Plots¶

The violin plots contrast the story told by the plot of mean revenues. While the mean values led us to believe that movie revenues were varying wildly over the years, these violin plots, with boxplots inside, show that the median revenues and the revenues for most films have stayed fairly consistent over the past century.
They also do an excellent job of highlighting how the maximum revenues of the decade have been steadily increasing since the 1980s, showing the ever-growing disparity between the highest-grossing blockbusters and the "average" movie revenue.

In [14]:

plt.show()

Plot 2.1.5 Rating vs Revenue Plot¶

Comparing revenue against ratings provided some very interesting trends.
Though a high rating does not guarantee a high revenue, a very low rating seems to be tied with low revenue.
We can't be sure whether low rating leads to lower revenues, or whether lower attendance/revenue contributed to lower ratings, but we would hypothesize the former.
Additionally, the highest revenues appear to increase as rating increases to 8, and then revenues seem to taper off some above that. This could be because "high art" very-highly rated films are not necessarily blockbusters or interest only a niche crowd, thus having modest revenues in spite of a high rating.
Because of this, the relationship is not purely linear, and the relationship may be better described by a higher power function.

Part 2.2: Analyzing trends accross Genre¶

There are a lot of ways in which movies can differ accross genre. For instance the average budget for an action/adventure movie will most likely be much higher than the average budget for a documentary. To split our data by genre, we will have to do some manipulating.

First, we will convert our genre column into a workable version:

In [20]:
#Reset index 
imdb_table = imdb_table.reset_index()
#Convert genre column into a column of arrays
genre_list = imdb_table['Genre'].map(lambda x: x.split(','))
imdb_table['Genre'] = genre_list

all_genres = []

#list of all genre tags from every movie
for i in range(len(genre_list)):
    all_genres = all_genres + genre_list[i]
    
#list of all unique genres
all_genres = pd.DataFrame(data=all_genres, columns={'genre'}).genre.unique()

Now we have the list of all genres that appear in our dataset:

all_genres

Now we'll define a few functions to help our analysis. The first filters our data into the chunks where a given genre occurs, the second will be used to plot relevant data about genres.

In [21]:
#Takes a list of genres, and a dataframe of movie entries
#Returns dataframe with only movies that include genre tags in genres parameter
def filter_by_genre(genres, df):
    if len(genres) > 0 :
        line = df['Genre'].map(lambda x: True if genres[0] in x else False )
        return filter_by_genre(genres[1:], df[line])
    else :
        return df

#Takes a list of genres, a table, x param and y param
#Plots features for movies with genres in genres param
def plot_genre_attributes(genres, table, xIn, yIn):
    genre_df = filter_by_genre(genres, table)
    sns.scatterplot(x=xIn, y=yIn, data=genre_df)
    string = ''.join( x + " " for x in genres)
    
    plt.title(string + " movies: " + yIn + " vs. " + xIn)
    plt.xlabel(xIn)
    plt.ylabel(yIn)
    plt.show()

For the previous point, now we can try and see the difference in average movie budget between action/adventure and documentary movies

In [22]:
action = filter_by_genre(['Action', 'Adventure'], imdb_table)
documentary = filter_by_genre(['Documentary'], imdb_table)
action_avg = np.sum(action['budget'])/len(action)
doc_avg = np.sum(documentary['budget'])/len(documentary)

print("Average budget for an Action/Adventure Movie: $", action_avg)
print("Average budget for a Documentary: $", doc_avg)
print("Average difference: $", action_avg-doc_avg)

Average budget for an Action/Adventure Movie: $ 83054732.4706
Average budget for a Documentary: $ 3764913.46281
Average difference: $ 79289819.0078

As we can see this confirms our hypothesis proposed above that the average budget for an Action/Adventure movie is greater than the budget for a documentary. In fact there is a difference of nearly 80 million dollars.

Part 3: Analysis, Hypothesis testing, & ML¶

Part 3.1: Linear Regression Analysis¶

Part 3.1.1: User Rating vs imdb rating¶

Now, lets create a linear model of user rating vs imbd rating. We can use this model to predict a imdb rating based on the average user rating. Or on the flip side, we can hypothesize what the average viewer will rate a movie based on what IMDB rated.

In [30]:
#This model will use user ratings as the x values, and imdb as the y

model1 = LinearRegression()
X = user_ratings_avg[['avg_rating']]
y = user_ratings_avg[["Rating"]]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y)
model1.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(model1.coef_)
print(model1.intercept_)

[[ 0.51101382]]
[ 3.36037905]

Now the have a model, lets see that previous scatterplot again this time with a linear regression line. Reminder, each point represents a different movie

In [31]:
plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
ax = sns.scatterplot(x='avg_rating', y='Rating', data=user_ratings_avg)
ax.set(xlabel='Average User Rating', ylabel='IMDB Rating', title='How user ratings match up against IMDB',)
plt.plot(X_test, model1.predict(X_test), color='red', linewidth=3)
#plt.show()
Out[31]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f66e1e1edd8>]

From the above plot, we can see that the average user rating of a movie is less than the imdb rating for the same movie. This holds true for the lower range of values, but it appears that as movie ratings increase, the two ratings agree more and more. Users and imdb critics alike seem to agree that good movies are good movies. It is important to note, however, that there are several user ratings of value 10, a ratings that is nonexistent among imdb ratings. This may skew our model, but in there definitely appears to be a linear relationship though, and with a coeficient of ~.5, we can see the relations is fairly strong. We can explore this more via a plot of the residuals.

In [32]:
residual_df = pd.concat([X_test,(y_test - model1.predict(X_test))], axis=1) #calculate the residual df
plt.subplots(figsize=(12,7))
ax = sns.regplot(data=residual_df,x='avg_rating',y='Rating')
ax.set(xlabel='User Rating', ylabel='Residual', title='Scatter Plot of Residuals')
#plt.show()

[Text(0,0.5,'Residual'),
 Text(0.5,0,'User Rating'),
 Text(0.5,1,'Scatter Plot of Residuals')]

This scatterplot shows the difference between predictions. We can see that there is no visual trend between ratings and residuals which is good. This shows that a linear model is indeed the best type of model to represent this relationship. In agreement with the above plot, we can see the residuals are very small when dealing with movies that users rated in the 5-7 range. It appears although people may have different ideas about what makes a bad and great movie, they agree upon which movies are just 'good'. It may be also that 5-7 is a very middle of the road rating and there are alot of movies with ratings of 5-7 by both imdb and the average user.

Part 3.2: Market Basket Analysis¶

To understand how genres are assigned to movies throughout our data, we can use a technique called "market basket analysis," where essentially the correlation value between sets of values are computed. First enter the following command in your terminal to download the libraries needed:

pip install mlxtend

We will need to import the following libraries:

In [36]:
from mlxtend.frequent_patterns import apriori
from mlxtend.frequent_patterns import association_rules

Now we need to "1-hot-encode" our genre data so that it can be processed. In other words we are creating columns in our dataset for every genre variable and filling the columns with 1 where the genre tag appears, and 0 where it does not.

In [37]:
#Instantiate matrix of 0's
genres = pd.DataFrame(data=genre_list)
for x in all_genres:
    genres[x] = 0
del genres['Genre']

#assign genre columns to one where they appear in a movie
for i in range(len(genre_list)):
    for j in genre_list[i]:
        genres[j][i] = 1

Below we compute the association rules between each set of two genres. The support value is the fraction of the number of movies with both genre tags / total_num_movies. If this value is greater than 0.7 the tags will be included in our table.

In [38]:
frequent_genre_sets = apriori(genres, min_support=0.07, use_colnames=True)
rules = association_rules(frequent_genre_sets, metric="lift", min_threshold=0)

Now we have our table of association values for all our genres:

rules.sort_values(by='support', ascending=False)
